Fall Shelf Styling REVEAL...⁣
⁣
If you saw my stories the past couple of days then you know I have been switching up my dining room shelves for fall!  I hope you are ready, because I took you along on the entire messy process!  Good thing I will only have to make small adjustments over the next few months to alter the decor for the different seasons and holidays!!⁣

Also, as I mentioned, I’ve teamed up with 4 talented friends to bring you some great shelf styling inspiration! ⁣

I know that I have mentioned before that I often times struggle with styling shelves.  It’s hard for me to find a balance between too many items, not enough items, and the right selection of pieces. I am finally happy with the way my dining room shelves have turned out, and I wanted to share with you some of the strategies that I used to create a simple, balanced and carefully curated look. 
I now have a link in my bio for you to easily access my @LIKEtoKNOW.it, Amazon Store, and my Pinterest page!  Now you can quickly and easily shop my home.

node.text:
Looking to add warmth and detail to a space?⁣
⁣
⁣
In 2 hours, and an investment of less than $50, this beautiful beam that I found at a lumber yard dramatically changed the look and feel of our entire kitchen. I lightly sanded the raw natural unstained beam, predrilled holes for the 6” deck screws, removed the drywall, and mounted to the studs in the wall. We also had some minor drywall repair around the beam as well. ⁣
⁣
For a small investment of time and money our Kitchen now has a more custom feel.  I love the added natural element and detail that the raw wood adds to the space. This is something you could also do for a fireplace mantle or even doorway to add custom details to your home!⁣
⁣
Head to the link in my BIO to SHOP this REEL by selecting SHOP my HOME!⁣
⁣

TOP 5 AMAZON in my home : Part One⁣
⁣
⁣
I have so many Amazon pieces in my home that it was hard to choose so I decided to start with my most asked about and Best Sellers from this year!⁣
⁣
48” Chandelier:  My linear Dining Room light is actually from RH, but I prefer the muted gold tone of this Dupe over the real deal.  At 1/4 of the price of other retailers this statement light is a must buy!⁣
⁣
8’ Mantel Beam:  We had custom brackets made to attach this raw wood beam over our fireplace. It added just the right natural element to our Great Room. ⁣
⁣
Faux Boxwoods:  I am generally a real plant kind of girl, but these faux shrubs just might be my favorite purchase of 2021!  No watering, no wet front porch, no dead leaves…they are pretty much perfect!  They will also be beautiful with holiday lights on!  Last week in Seattle large boxwoods similar to these lined the front of the 5 story RH Store. ⁣
⁣
Faux Linen Panels:  These curtain panels were my Top Seller in 2020 and 2021!  I have two versions in my home that are not only beautiful, but more affordable!⁣
⁣
Wood Saddle Stool:  I really wanted a cute wood stool for our new bathroom, but I didn’t want to spend $150+. For $40 I decided to give this beauty a try and had planned on beating it up a bit, but it was perfect just as it is!⁣
⁣
⁣
Stay tuned for more Amazon in my Home. Want to Shop my Home?  Link in Bio. Make sure to Follow me on my Amazon Storefront and LIKEtoKNOW.it! ⁣

node.text:
“Do you use all new pieces each time you style your shelves?”⁣
⁣
⁣
This is one of the questions that I was asked after my Shelf Styling series last week, and the answer is no. I have three sets of open shelving in my home…The Dining Room, Laundry Room, and in our Primary Bedroom. I also have two cabinets with glass doors that I style. The only area that I typically restyle completely each season is my Dining Room shelves. They are such a focal point in our home that I enjoy changing them up almost entirely,  otherwise I only swap out a couple different pieces in the other areas. ⁣
⁣
I just recently changed up My Primary Bedroom shelves and decided to add in a black vase and bowl for a moody vibe, and swapped in a new Target bowl and seasonal faux stems. Just a few minor changes completely changed the look and feel of this entire space. Once I create a balance that I love I don’t like to mess it up too much. 😉 ⁣
⁣
Make sure to follow me on the @shop.LTK to Shop my Home. Link in BIO. ⁣

Home Style/Design/Build Part 2⁣
⁣
⁣
Though some finishing details are easier to complete during your new build or remodel, many can be added after you have moved in to create a custom feel in your home.⁣
⁣
Here are the spaces that we currently have added finishing details to:⁣
⁣
1.  Customized Trim and Baseboards:  We added additional trim pieces around our door and window trim to create a more detailed look and to make the doors and windows appear larger.  The trim piece at the base of the base board create a finished look and a more substantial baseboard. ⁣
⁣
2.  Trim Detail:  Adding simple Wall Moulding in our Dining Room and Primary Bedroom added a detail that is beautiful as it is, or it creates a frame for wreaths and art work in those spaces.⁣
⁣
3.  Shiplap:  We added shiplap to the ceiling in our Kitchen, Entry, and Hallway.  The Shiplap creates visual interest and breaks up our lower ceiling areas.  The 10” horizontal MDF boards flanking the fireplace added a subtle backdrop to mirrors and picture lights, while the 6” horizontal shiplap in our tween boys room completely changed the space. ⁣
⁣
The Kitchen Shiplap ceiling was added during our remodel, while all of the other details were added afterwards. Home takes time. Don’t feel like everything has to be completed immediately…I still do not know what I want to do in some spaces.  Always a work on progress. 😉⁣

One of the biggest questions that I am asked is…⁣
⁣
⁣
“How do I add black/dark accents into my white and neutral home?”⁣
⁣
Black can actually be just as much of a neutral color as white and wood tones are. If you are looking to add darker accents and contrast to your home I always suggest that you start small, and that you add a few darker pieces throughout a couple of rooms to allow your home to feel cohesive. Vases, throws, pillows with subtle black accents, and rugs with a touch of black are a great way to introduce a little moody into your home. Darker wood tones and faux stems are another option for adding pops of contrast to your home without committing to black!⁣

SHELF STYLING: Part Two…⁣
⁣
⁣
As I mention during Part One, Shelf Styling can be intimidating.  What should I put on the shelves?  How many is too many items?  Does it look too busy?⁣
⁣
These are just a few of the thoughts that used to run through my head when styling shelves, and it always made me crazy!⁣
⁣
In addition to the Style Tips you will see throughout the video, there are two main concepts that I always follow…1. Scale and 2. Less is more. One of my biggest struggles had to do with shelves looking too cluttered.  I am not a knick knack king of girl. Once I narrowed down my colors and textures I knew I was headed in the right direction, but choosing larger items, and therefore less items, was the biggest game changer for me!  The pieces made a statement and created visual interest, but they didn’t clutter up my shelves or my brain!⁣
⁣

Home Remodel/Build  Part 1⁣
⁣
⁣
I am often asked why we decided to take on a major remodel project verses closing on the lot we had selected and already had plans drawn up for…we were 4 days from closing and building was set to begin.  Basically the minute I walked through the front door of our home…despite the orange toned wood and green and burgundy paint, I just knew this was it. We loved the location and the bones of the home were good!⁣
⁣
Now don’t get me wrong, I immediately started making my list of changes, but I knew this is where we were supposed to raise our family.⁣
⁣
When you remodel you definitely have limitations, just like any build, but there were things I knew I could not change in this home.  Soaring ceilings and a large spiral staircase were not in my future so I had to decide what I could do to this home to make it feel more custom. ⁣
⁣
Adding French Doors in our entryway, heading out to our deck, and in several rooms made our rooms feel larger, more connected to the spaces around them, and gave our home an elevated feel.  Instead of standard size single interior doors we oversized them to a 3’ x 8’ two panel door.  The larger size draws your eye up and make our ceilings feel higher and our home more grand.  Upgrading our doors is definitely one of the top 3 favorite changes that we made to our home.⁣
⁣
What other topics can I cover for you in regards to remodeling or building?  I have a lot to share with about our journey!  Ask away!⁣
